---
export const metadata = {
  title: "The Sound of Waves",
  author: "Yukio Mishima",
  year: 1954,
  rating: "★★★☆☆",

  summary:
    "A philosophical fantasy about memory, identity, and consciousness set within an infinite House of statues, tides, and collapsing perception.",
};

const title = metadata.title;
const author = metadata.author;
const year = metadata.year;
const rating = metadata.rating;

---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />

  <title>{title} Review</title>

  <style>
    :root {
      --bg: #f8f8f5;
      --text: #111;
      --muted: #666;
      --border: #d8d8d8;
      --max-width: 72ch;
    }

    html {
      scroll-behavior: smooth;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      background: var(--bg);
      color: var(--text);

      font-family: Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 19px;
      line-height: 1.72;

      padding: 3rem 1.5rem 6rem;
    }

    .container {
      max-width: var(--max-width);
      margin: 0 auto;
      position: relative;
    }

    h1 {
      font-size: 3rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: -0.03em;

      margin-bottom: 0.2rem;
    }

    .meta {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      font-family: monospace;

      margin-bottom: 3rem;
    }

    p {
      margin-bottom: 1.7rem;
      text-align: justify;
    }

    blockquote {
      margin: 2.5rem 0;
      padding-left: 1.2rem;

      border-left: 2px solid var(--border);

      color: #333;
      font-style: italic;
    }

    .section-break {
      text-align: center;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin: 3rem 0;
      letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    }

    .sidenote {
      float: right;
      clear: right;

      width: 15rem;

      margin-right: -18rem;
      margin-top: 0.3rem;

      padding-left: 0.9rem;
      border-left: 1px solid var(--border);

      color: var(--muted);

      font-size: 0.78rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }

    .sidenote code {
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      background: #efefea;
      padding: 0.05rem 0.2rem;
    }

    @media (max-width: 1200px) {
      .sidenote {
        display: none;
      }
    }

    a {
      color: inherit;
    }

    hr {
      border: none;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      margin: 4rem 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>
  <main class="container">

    <h1>{title}</h1>
    <div class="meta">
      Yukio Mishima · 1954 · {rating} [WIP Review]
    </div>
    <p> 
        <span> 
        Uta-Jima is an idyllic town unaffected by the changes of modernization. Shinji the protagnist has a blossoming love story with the female protagonist Hatsue. 
        The simplicity of the characters fits them into traditional japanese stereo-types and allows a simple, feel good story. 
        The whole book was simple, and steady like the tide. 
        </span>

        
        




    </p>
    <p> 
        Yukio Mishima embraces the traditional japanese values and his characters serve as ideals of japanese virtue. Shinji is a young man who pursues love while 
        revering traditional morality. Hatsue stays loyal to her love despite pressure while remaining a virtuous daughter. 
        </p>
        <p> 
            The prose style of the book ,a combination of Weatherby's translation skills and Mishima's original intent, is simply fitting. The prose is short and simple like a glass pane and 
            presents the important facts without over-description.
            The prose's best qualities are the use of concrete description, confidence and directness, and almost an ease in the way he tells the story. 
            The prose lacks the preformativeness of purple prose and this is analogous to japanese values. The residents of Uta-Jima value directness and work hard. Perhaps this glorification of 
            japanese values, stems from his background as a strong japanese-nationalist. 
        </p>
        <p> 
            z
            </p>
    </main>